# WHAT IT IS
#   `ldap_authz_proxy` runs as a small HTTP server listening (by
#   default) on `127.0.0.1:10567`.  It is meant to sit behind
#   Nginx + `ngx_http_auth_request_module` and implement the LDAP-
#   authorization slice of the standard "Kerberos-then-LDAP"
#   pattern that real production deployments use to gate access
#   to internal applications:
#
#     1. Nginx receives an HTTPS request and runs SPNEGO /
#        Kerberos / SAML / OIDC / any-other auth subsystem to
#        identify the user (so the upstream user is now known
#        to be e.g. `alice@CORP.EXAMPLE.ORG`).
#     2. Nginx makes a sub-request to `/auth` proxied to
#        `http://127.0.0.1:10567/<config-section>` with the
#        original user identity in a configurable header.
#     3. `ldap_authz_proxy` extracts the username from the
#        header, looks up the configured `[<section>]` in its
#        config file, performs an LDAP query (BIND with a
#        service account, then SEARCH the directory for the
#        user's groups + attributes), composes typed attribute
#        values into HTTP response headers (`X-User-Groups`,
#        `X-User-DN`, `X-User-Mail`, ...) per the config
#        section's `out_headers`, and returns HTTP 200 (or 403
#        if the user is not authorized).
#     4. Nginx receives the 200 + headers, forwards the
#        request to the actual upstream with the headers
#        attached, so the protected app sees the user's
#        LDAP-derived metadata without ever talking to LDAP
#        itself.
#
#   Built-in features:
#
#     • Per-section sub-query joining (`Any` / `All` / `Main`
#       — combine multiple LDAP queries into one authorization
#       decision with set-union, set-intersection, or
#       primary-only semantics)
#     • Per-section TTL LRU cache (sha256-keyed on
#       config-section-name + username + URI; default 60-second
#       TTL configurable per-section) to keep the LDAP server
#       lightly loaded
#     • Connection pooling is NOT yet implemented (TODO in
#       upstream); every cache miss creates a fresh LDAP
#       connection
#     • Dump-mode for config validation:
#       `ldap_authz_proxy --dump-config /etc/ldap_authz_proxy.conf`
#       parses the config and prints the resolved values
#       (useful for verifying that env-var expansion + INI
#       parsing produced what you expected)
#     • Test mode for one-shot authorization checks:
#       `ldap_authz_proxy -t /etc/ldap_authz_proxy.conf
#         alice@CORP.EXAMPLE.ORG /protected/path`
#       performs a single authorization query and exits with
#       0 (authorized — HTTP 200 equivalent) or the HTTP error
#       code (e.g. 403) — perfect for shell-script integration
#       and CI/CD pre-deploy checks
#     • Optional JSON-format structured logging via `-j --json`
#     • Optional log-file redirection via `-l --log FILE`
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from src/main.rs `USAGE`
#                       const docopt grammar; extracted via
#                       raw.githubusercontent.com fetch of
#                       src/main.rs)
#
#   Usage:
#     ldap_authz_proxy [OPTIONS] <CONFIG_FILE>
#     ldap_authz_proxy -t | --test [OPTIONS] <CONFIG_FILE>
#                                            <USERNAME> <URI_PATH>
#     ldap_authz_proxy -h | --help
#     ldap_authz_proxy -H | --help-config
#     ldap_authz_proxy -v | --version
#
#   Required:
#     <CONFIG_FILE>                  Path to the INI configuration
